          "body": "Verses 21-24 contain Job's most theologically explosive claims. 'It is all one; therefore I say, He destroys the guiltless and the wicked' (9:22). 'He mocks the despair of the innocent' (9:23). 'The earth is given into the hand of the wicked; He covers the faces of its judges' (9:24). The temptation is to explain these verses away, but that approach fails on two counts. Canonically, God Himself later vindicates Job's speech as more right than his friends' (42:7), which means these verses cannot be simply dismissed as sinful error. Theologically, what Job is articulating — from within unrelenting pain and the appearance of divine absence — is not atheism or blasphemy but the raw phenomenology of a world in which retributive justice does not function with the mechanical precision Bildad promised. Calvin (Sermons on Job) noted that the friends spoke orthodoxly but falsely, while Job spoke roughly but truly. The difference is the difference between systematic theology applied from outside suffering and theology wrested from inside it."
