        "title": "Conceding the premise to expose the problem — how can a mortal be right before God?",
        "range": "9:2-4",
        "excerpt": "In truth I know that this is so; but how can a man be in the right before God? If one wished to dispute with Him, he could not answer Him once in a thousand times.",
        "body": "Job's opening move is strategically brilliant: he concedes Bildad's central premise (God is just) before demolishing the comfort that premise was supposed to offer. The affirmation 'In truth I know that this is so' (9:2a) echoes Bildad's rhetorical question in 8:3 — 'Does God pervert justice?' Job is saying: correct, He does not. But the concession immediately leads to a question that exposes the premise's pastoral uselessness: 'But how can a man be in the right before God?'\n\nThe word *tsadaq* (to be righteous, to be in the right) is the pivotal term. It is not primarily a moral term here but a forensic one — to be vindicated in court, to have one's case established before a judge. Job is not asking whether God is morally just in the abstract; he is asking whether the mechanism exists by which a mortal can access that justice. The answer in verse 3 is devastating: if he wished to dispute, he could not answer God even once in a thousand attempts. The ratio — one in a thousand — is a Hebrew idiom for overwhelming disparity (cf. Ecclesiastes 7:28), not a precise statistic. The point is absolute: the disparity of power and wisdom is so great that legal discourse on equal terms is impossible.\n\nThe characterization in verse 4 — 'Wise in heart and mighty in strength, who has defied Him without harm?' — is both affirmation and warning. It is the same combination Paul deploys in Romans 11:33-34 when he marvels at the depth of God's wisdom and knowledge. But here the function is not doxological; it is argumentative. The wisdom-and-power combination ensures that no opponent of God's decisions has ever successfully challenged them and survived. The chapter has not yet offered any comfort; it has only established the parameters of the problem.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsadaq* is the forensic root of the entire chapter's legal argument — it does not mean merely 'be good' but 'be established as right in a legal proceeding.' *Enosh* (mortal man, v.2) stresses human frailty and finitude — a weaker word than *ish* (man in his strength, v.32), deliberately chosen to emphasize the power asymmetry."
